Introduction¶

For the purpose of this project, the Ford GoBike System Data is the chosen dataset. This dataset contains data pertaining to the greater San Francisco Bay area for individual rides made in a bike-sharing system.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

  • There are 183412 rows and 16 columns.

The columns include:-

  • duration_sec - total duration of trip in sec
  • start_time - timestamp of start of trip
  • end_time - timestamp of start of trip
  • start_station_id - it contains 197 null values
  • start_station_name - it contains 197 null values
  • start_station_latitude
  • start_station_longitude
  • end_station_id - it contains 197 null values
  • end_station_name - it contains 197 null values
  • end_station_latitude
  • end_station_longitude
  • bike_id - ids of each bike
  • user_type - user type of Subscriber or Customer.
  • member_birth_year - it contains 8265 null values
  • member_gender - gender of member in a trip. it also contains 8265 null values
  • bike_share_for_all_trip - Yes/No

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

1) I'm interested in figuring out patterns in the number of trips taken in terms of time of day, day of week, by creating new columns start_hour, start_day_of_week.
2) The average length of duration of trips concerning column duration_sec.
3) I also want to check if the above varies depending on user_type, member_gender & bike_share_for_all_trip.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

1) For the first point of interest creating new separate date, time & day column will be beneficial.
2) Plotting mean of duration_sec will help answer the second point
3) bivariate & multivariate plots would be essential in finding out any hidden patterns.

# creating 1 figure and 1 subplot
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize=(10,5), dpi=250)
# assigning main title to figure
fig.suptitle("Start Hour Distribution", fontsize=16)
# histogram plot
sns.histplot(x='start_hour', data=df_clean, kde=True)
# marking red dotted line on 8th hour
axes.axvline(8, color="red", linestyle="--")
# commenting on 8th hour
axes.text(x=6.9, y=17500, s="8th hr", color="red")
# marking red dotted line on 17th hour
axes.axvline(17, color="red", linestyle="--")
# commenting on 17th hour
axes.text(x=17.1, y=17500, s="17th hr", color="red")
# adjust the layout to use the least amount of space
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('images/start_hr_dist.png');
  • There are 2 peaks in the 'start_hour' column, i.e., around the 8th and the 17th hour there are more number of trips. So, the morning around 8 am and the evening around 5 pm are the two busiest start times, which may indicated that these are the office start and end times.

x_value = axes[1].lines[0].get_xdata()[np.where(axes[1].lines[0].get_ydata() >= 0.97)][0]
axes[1].axhline(0.97, color="red", linestyle="--")
axes[1].axvline(x_value, color="red", linestyle="--")
axes[1].text(x=x_value+100, y=0.85, s=f"97th persentile = {x_value}", color="orange")

axes[0].set_title("Trip Duration (in sec) histogram plot")
axes[1].set_title("Trip Duration (in sec) cummulative distribution plot")

Multivariate Exploration¶

creating morning, afternoon, evening and night time of the day column

In [62]:
# defining the time of the day function
def timeofday(time):
    if time >= 6 and time < 12:
        return "Morning"
    elif time >=12 and time < 16:
        return "Afternoon"
    elif time >=16 and time < 19:
        return "Evening"
    else:
        return "Night"
In [63]:
# creating the time of day column
df_clean["time_of_day"] = df_clean.start_hour.apply(timeofday)

Conclusions¶

After exploring the data I have concluded with the below points:-

  • It is seen that 'duration_sec' distribution is right skewed.
  • 97% of the trips are shorter than 1905 sec (or 31.75 mins).
  • There are 2 peaks in the 'start_hour' column, i.e., around the 8th and the 17th hour there are more number of trips. So, the morning around 8 am and the evening around 5 pm are the two busiest start times, which may indicated that these are the office start and end hours.
  • Thursday seems to be the day of week which has the most number of trips, followed by Tuesday and Wednesday.
  • During weekends/offdays the number of trips are almost half of that during working day.
  • Average trip duration is 704 secs (or 11.7 minutes).
  • Subscribers are significantly using more bikes than customers.
  • Males users are more than Females followed by other gender.
  • Users who do bike share are significantly lower than who don't do bike share.
  • Customer user type are using the bike service for more time duration than Subscribers.
  • The 'Other' gender is using has more seconds of trip duration, followed by females and surprisingly last is the male.
  • From the lineplot, its clear that during the weekends bike users travel for longer duration.
  • Even though users who do bike share are significantly less than who don't, the median value of duration of each category (Yes/No) is closeby (about 500). This indicated that users who use bike share are using it for longer duration.
  • It seems that longer durations trips occur after midnight (0th hour/12am) and before morning (around 4:30/5am).
  • The 'Other' gender uses the bike for longer duration as opposed to Male & Female gender.
  • The 'Other' gender takes longer duration on Monday, Wednesday & Thursday.
  • The 'Other' gender which doesn't share bike goes for longer duration are all Customers.
  • On average no Subscriber has taken longer duration trips than Customers.

While doing the above:-

  • All the null values were removed in order to plot distribution of only those records which were complete.
  • Datatypes of some columns were changed in order to facilitate proper analysis.
  • Some new columns were created like start_hour, start_day_of_week, etc.

There were some interesting points as follows:-

  • The 'Other' gender is not clear/specific.
  • Bike users who share bike are using it for longer duration.
  • While Males are dominating gender, they are not the users who travel for more duration, infact they travel least duration.
  • Interestingly, no customers did bike share. Only subscribers did bikeshare.

Further Research scope¶

Further research can be done by:-

  • Calculating age of the users and exploring its feature against other features to get more insights into users of different age groups.
  • Distance can be calculated from the latitude and longitude and further relations between the station and time taken and speed could be found out to dig deeper into user behaviours.
